\section{Monte Carlo bias, and computing an unbiased estimate yourself}{

With \code{deterministic = FALSE}, the returned \code{index} is a biased
estimate of \code{1 - R}: a finite sample's resultant length is never
exactly zero, so it systematically overestimates a small true \code{R},
and near-balanced shapes score slightly LOW - by up to roughly
\code{1/sqrt(n_lines)} for an exactly balanced shape (about 0.018 at the
default \code{n_lines = 3000}), shrinking as the true \code{R} grows or as
\code{n_lines} increases. This cannot be corrected away on the \code{1 - R}
scale: no unbiased estimator of \code{1 - R} exists for any finite
sample, for the same structural reason a sample standard deviation
cannot be unbiased even though a sample variance can.

What does admit an exactly unbiased estimate is the closely related
\code{1 - R^2} (the same quantity on a squared scale: same \verb{[0, 1]}
range, same direction, same shapes scoring exactly 1). Compute it
yourself from the returned \code{R}:
\code{1 - (n_lines * R^2 - 1) / (n_lines - 1)}.
This is exactly unbiased for \code{1 - R^2} - any weight distribution,
any \code{n_lines >= 2} - and is the right quantity to average or compare
across many near-balanced shapes in a batch. It can land slightly
above 1 for near-balanced shapes; that is a necessary feature, not
an error (no estimator confined to \verb{[0, 1]} can be unbiased at the
boundary), so do not truncate it back to 1 if unbiasedness is the
point.

\code{deterministic = TRUE} carries no statistical bias at all - only
deterministic quadrature error, which shrinks with mesh resolution.
